00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:04.080
- [Margaret] Welcome. We begin another
extremely interesting session with some

00:02:04.080 --> 00:02:09.780
very promising speakers in front of me.
I'm Margaret Schoeninger, I'm co-director,

00:02:09.780 --> 00:02:14.700
one of the co-directors, of CARTA and I
just, again, want to say welcome. For

00:02:14.700 --> 00:02:20.780
CARTA, as the video was portraying, we're
very interested in the oldest questions of

00:02:20.780 --> 00:02:27.090
humans. So what we're looking at is who
are we? What are we doing here? We all are

00:02:27.090 --> 00:02:32.590
interested in in this. Where do we come
from? How did we get here? Where are we

00:02:32.590 --> 00:02:38.440
going? But there're only really two
questions of that list that we can begin

00:02:38.440 --> 00:02:46.810
to really address scientifically, really
collect data on them. So that's why CARTA

00:02:46.810 --> 00:02:54.210
was formed. CARTA is anthropogeny and it
is trying to explain the origin of humans.

00:02:54.210 --> 00:02:59.660
It's from an old dictionary saying, an
Oxford dictionary in 2006 actually put it

00:02:59.660 --> 00:03:05.420
